text:
looking within
i have always loved wood knots. the marks in the trunk where branches died. the imperfections that many try to fill in or sand down to cover the mark of what used to be.  however, i never saw them as blemishes, i saw them as the entry into the soul of the trees, souls of the walls or flooring they covered. as a young child i would scan the room searching for the knots. my body frozen, i would see the eye in the cedar paneling and trace its oval markings. i would count the grooves, notice the different shades and rippled markings. i would escape the pain, the fear, the smell and hide inside the knot. i didn‚Äôt have to feel inside the knot. the knots bore witness to what happened in that room. the knots became the doorways to escape. the giant eyes would capture my thoughts and worries and hold space until it stopped. today, i still find beauty and comfort in wood knots. i am often marveled at the joy i feel when a surprise knot catches my eye and we stare at each other and hold space in a peaceful way as if to say ‚Äúhello old soul you‚Äôre always welcomed to come inside.‚Äù
name: Genevieve Denise

text:
once a male hypothalamus is flooded with copulins, the male brain is just sitting on idle (doing nothing), with only the bare minimum of thought process.
 any input from the female will become the male's singular focus.
 during coupling, female can vocally change what the male perceives and/or remembers.  female can vocally:
- change, remove, or insert memories
- tell the male what he sees, hears, feels, smells, tastes
- insert subconscious thoughts that will surface as male "ideas" or behaviour later - plant trigger words or actions that can cause thoughts, actions, or sensations in the male at the later dates (days, weeks, even months)

text: today her turns 2! i want to take today to explain a little bit about her and to thank each and everyone of you. in april of 2016, i ended my abusive relationship. all spring and summer, i was fighting hard to deal with the pain, but even though i knew what happened to me, i didn‚Äôt know there was a name for the hurt i had endured. a male friend of mine told me i should seek out the services of @havenmt ‚Äîthe women‚Äôs shelter in my town. i was hesitant at first. i didn‚Äôt see myself as a victim. but i got tired of bawling my eyes out in the shower so my roommate wouldn‚Äôt see how hurt i was. i got tired of drinking on work nights so that i could focus on something other than the negative thoughts in my own mind. i reached out to haven and joined their end the silence group where i met other survivors and was able to be vulnerable for the first time. i realized there was power in my story and their was power in breaking my silence. i wanted every survivor to have the same opportunity i was given. i wanted everyone to have community‚Äîwhether they wanted to stay anonymous or not. so on october 1, 2016, 5 survivors courageously shared their story on the website weareher.net. since then, her has grown across the united states and even to asia and europe. i‚Äôve held events and spoken at schools. her is a micro community that continues to grow for survivors everywhere. i am so grateful to each and everyone of you. i hope her helps you feel safe. i hope you know you can message me at anytime of the day or night. you are like family to me and i am so grateful everyday for every like, every comment, every word of encouragement you all give to keep each other inspired and empowered. it only takes a little change to make the world a better place, and each of you do that everyday when you become her. so from the bottom of my heart, thank you. all my her love, stevie üíôüíú

beauty & the blood: mother and child 1/3, 2018 || creating a culture that understands menstruation, rather women and girls, begins with honest education for both girls and boys. when you learned about menstruation in sex ed class, were you separated from the boys? i was. why are they not a part of the conversation? boys and men alike should be held accountable for the negative stigma that surrounds menstruation. with more honest education we can build a culture where women are valued and are not shamed or forced to hide and whisper about a natural bodily function. furthermore, a culture where women and girls are not forced to hide and whisper about anything that happens to them and their body because it does matter. all women matter. all girls matter. this work is dedicated to my daughters. üì∏: @jac000b .

text:
disclaimer: in light of the national conversations we are having about the impact that sexual victimization has and the shame and embarrassment that comes with it, i did not share my story to shame anyone or embarrass anyone or point fingers.  please if you can, let‚Äôs not pass judgement and think with compassion. i do a lot of teaching, training, writing and youth work around institutional trauma and its impact on the oppression of black and brown communities.  my passion is to work with communities to brainstorm ways of looking at violence from a mental health and public health standpoint.  generational trauma is something that we often discuss in our work with the community and partnering agencies because of its deep impact on our future generations.  but my real focus is to work with individual trauma in my youth work because i know what it feels like to feel alone. i think my own narrative is why i relate to young people with similar experiences in such a meaningful way and allows me to see strengths and build on resilience in my own work. i began sharing my story for my own healing and to partner with youth who are experiencing the same emotions i have gone through and sometimes still struggle with. this interview was me being mostly transparent because i think all that i have gone through is part of my journey and made me who i am today. i am still healing, my family is still healing our journey does not end here and there is always room to improve.  i believe my divine purpose is to live by example and do my best to bring awareness and partner with others to bring innovative culturally appropriate methods of healing.  i think incarceration, tough on crime approaches only revictimizes those who have already suffered enough and more text: it's the first day of inktober! this day is a strange one as the word is poisonous. with everything going on with kavanaugh and the continuance of the me too movement my mind went to poisonous/toxic relationships. i sat down for hours thinking of which character of mine to draw, only to realize that none of them have a toxic romantic relationship. so instead, this came to fruition. it's something my mind has been battling for years internally and is something that i'm still trying to understand and grasp every day. shoving away certain things does not fix an issue, you have to eventually confront it. #metoo #inktober #inktober2018 #poisonous #toxic #relationships #micronpen #learningartist #jaxoline.art #college #highschool

text:
ana maria archila (pictured) revealed she was sexually assaulted as a child by a teenager and maria gallagher revealed she was a survivor of sexual abuse.
*
we sparked the fbi kavanaugh probe! assault survivors, who confronted jeff flake in an elevator before his senate flip-flop, take credit for changing his vote - as one reveals she shared story of her attack for the first time in now viral shutdown - part 3/6
*
gallagher shouted, through tears: 'i was sexually assaulted and nobody believed me.'
*
'i didn't tell anyone, and you're telling all women that they don't matter, that they should just stay quiet because if they tell you what happened to them you are going to ignore them.'
*
"that's what happened to me, and that's what you're telling all women in america, that they don't matter," she said through tears.
*
after the heated exchange, flake announced that he would advance kavanaugh's nomination but only after the fbi be allowed to investigate the allegations against kavanaugh by dr blasey ford.
*
reacting to flake's volte-face, gallagher said she felt relieved that their voices had been heard and that an fbi investigation will take place.
*
she told the daily beast: 'we all ran after him. we held open the elevator and i just started telling him why it was important and what had happened to me and why he should not let brett kavanaugh on the supreme court.'
*
'he wouldn't meet my eyes. it made me very angry. he kept saying thank you and i'm sorry and wasn't taking into account what his actions would be doing to millions of people and what this means for everyone.'
(to be continued)
*
leah mcdonald, daily mail and associated press 29 september 2018
*

text:
disclaimer: in light of the national conversations we are having about the impact that sexual victimization has and the shame and embarrassment that comes with it, i did not share my story to shame anyone or embarrass anyone or point fingers.  please if you can, let‚Äôs not pass judgement and think with compassion. i do a lot of teaching, training, writing and youth work around institutional trauma and its impact on the oppression of black and brown communities.  my passion is to work with communities to brainstorm ways of looking at violence from a mental health and public health standpoint.  generational trauma is something that we often discuss in our work with the community and partnering agencies because of its deep impact on our future generations.  but my real focus is to work with individual trauma in my youth work because i know what it feels like to feel alone. i think my own narrative is why i relate to young people with similar experiences in such a meaningful way and allows me to see strengths and build on resilience in my own work. i began sharing my story for my own healing and to partner with youth who are experiencing the same emotions i have gone through and sometimes still struggle with. this interview was me being mostly transparent because i think all that i have gone through is part of my journey and made me who i am today. i am still healing, my family is still healing our journey does not end here and there is always room to improve.  i believe my divine purpose is to live by example and do my best to bring awareness and partner with others to bring innovative culturally appropriate methods of healing.  i think incarceration, tough on crime approaches only revictimizes those who have already suffered enough and more compassion and healing has to be at the forefront of what we do as a society to address pain. i had the opportunity to share my story with an amazing woman and counselor who has embarked on a journey to share also follow this amazing queen @emergecounselingandcoaching 
#mentalhealth #meditation #healing https://emergecounselingnj.com/index.php/2018/10/01/story1-yougotthis-the-woman-who-is-reimagining-justice/
#metoo

text:
vulnerable post for anyone else who is going through something similar as well as create some accountability for my own self care.
#metoo is not something i posted when it first started, even though it is true. i still feel shame and i don't want to make others feel uncomfortable. i recognize that it shouldn't be my responsibility to apologize for something that happened to me, but it is unfortunately a feeling i've yet to totally conquer.
however, the fact is that i had an experience where something was taken from me that i can't get back. it's not responsibility to apologize for that, but it has been my responsibility to fill that gap with love, which is not a task that has an end date. when i don't, that void starts to swallow me whole and suck everything i love and worked for in with it. 
i've had a very hard past few weeks. i have been incredibly stressed out, burnt out, and depleted of energy trying to accomplish a lot of tasks in a very short amount of time with not enough resources. i have been running myself thin and not taking the time to take care of myself. my efforts to unwind have been more like efforts to escape than to nurture.
recently, and kind of suddenly, i have been reliving a lot of feelings i haven‚Äôt felt in a long time. when i reflect on what's different in my life that's dredging this stuff up, it becomes glaringly obvious that i simply have not been loving myself. i have been holding myself to unreasonably high expectations and straining to keep everything in order so that i can look around and feel that if everything appears tidy and together, then it is. lately, everything i have been doing has been to further my to-do list, rather than my well being.
i'm sharing this because i know from talking to other women that this shit feels impossible sometimes. if you're feeling like i'm feeling, please remember that you are complete and whole right now; that you don't owe anything to anyone; that if you have a story to tell, it is yours to tell when you want to or not tell if you don't want to. most importantly, take care of yourself.
let your house get a little messy, watch some shitty tv, eat some carbs.
i am here with you and for you.

text:
picked up this little souvenir!  anyone that knows me well, knows i struggled to come to terms with this. i have been sober from heroin for 3yrs 7mos & 22 days. but not knowing there was a system in place to help restore me to sanity & find true recovery by following certain steps, i thought i could drink successfully.
‚Ä¢
i did for a time, but this disease  is cunning & patient. it waited until my guard was down & under the influence of alcohol told me ‚Äúyou know this isn‚Äôt what you want...let‚Äôs go get what you really want‚Äù. it was enough to scare me to not pick up a drink again. that was a year ago.
‚Ä¢
in that years time, i started going to a meeting, but still not understanding the process thought that was enough. one meeting a week with no step work & no sponsor.  6mos ago, my world was flipped upside down. what happened that day had a tremendous impact on my life, but not for reasons most may think. what started as a tragic event became the turning point in my recovery as well.
‚Ä¢
i was alone & angry & depressed & i didn‚Äôt hide that. but then i accepted god & surrendered my life & will to him. i met my two best friends shortly after losing my ultimate best friend.  i started attending more meetings each week & have an amazing sponsor. she found me...i was drawn to her & terrified of her at the same time, but knew she would push me way out of my comfort zone, which is what i needed. i made a real transition from staying sober to finding recovery & the shift has been awesome.
‚Ä¢
i‚Äôm not saying it has all been roses & butterflies bc it hasn‚Äôt been. it‚Äôs been an ugly, scary, emotional roller coaster that i wouldn‚Äôt trade for anything bc my worst days in recovery are still way better then my best days in active addiction.
‚Ä¢
can‚Äôt wait to celebrate with my sponsor & others at our celebration meeting at the end of the month. it will be the first time i will get a coin to carry around with me...it may not be much to some, but it means so much to me!
‚Ä¢
#faithhopelove #teamburninitdown #soberversary #oneyearsober #recoveryispossible

text:
nine and a half. 
i was nine and a half when it started. 
if i can‚Äôt speak my truth, how can i expect others to speak theirs?  how can i expect that my son or daughter will someday feel comfortable enough to reach out for help if they need it? if they are afraid or embarrassed, hurt or confused?

social media, as of late, has made it hard for me to forget. the incredible amount of shame and fear i feel as i write this is insurmountable; i fear what people will think of me, people who have known me my entire life and people i‚Äôve known for only a few weeks, and i fear being judged.  i‚Äôm ashamed of being the person it happened to and in how it happened more than once over such a long period of time by a person my family trusted. perhaps the two feelings play off of one another. these feelings lead me to wonder if ‚Äòforgetting‚Äô is even the answer. 
i don‚Äôt know what‚Äôs true or false in social media and the news these days; i know my truth.  i, in no way, want sympathy or attention and i don‚Äôt want to talk about any further about the details‚Äîi‚Äôd honestly rather keep this buried like it has been for so many years. my hope in sharing this is that maybe, one day, we can eliminate this stigma and lead by example for future generations by being supportive, open, unbiased, warm people and genuinely caring for one another, by teaching our children that it‚Äôs ok to talk to us, to have inner strength, as well as mutual respect and morality for all living creatures‚Äînot by telling them, but by showing them. 
we may never be able to fully stop things like this from happening to others, but we can change what happens next for them. i want to be the change i wish to see in the world my children live in: maybe it starts here... #metoo #soulcleansing #speakout #killingthestigma #childrenarethefuture #respect #breakthesilence #findsupport

text:
this campaign is going on on facebook.
and while i try not to be super political on social media this is something that is very important, and very personal to me.
*
i am a survivor.
*
i was sexually assaulted when i was 16 years old.  i told my parents and talked to a lawyer.  she told me it was a waste of time.  so when i was assaulted again at 17 i didn't tell anyone... why bother?  nothing would be done anyway.
*
i am also a survivor of domestic violence.  my first husband had a lot of problems and i became the target.  he was emotionally abusive, cheated on me endlessly, and then was physically aggressive.  i called the cops on him more than once. 
nothing happened but a night in jail to "cool off". it took a long time for me to get up the courage to leave.  but i did with the love and support of my parents.  i call it my "previous life" because i left pretty much all of it behind.  there are very few people in my life now that were part of that world.
*
i stand in solidarity with my sisters and brothers who survive. 
we are called survivors because our assailants didn't kill us, and we didn't take our own lives after the fact.  we are taking back our own lives, our own strength, our own power.
*
this is not a commentary on the current political climate. 
it 
is
my
reality.
*
and if it helps one person, one individual know they are not alone, they are not forgotten, there is life and beauty and strength on the other side, then it is totally and completely worth it.
name: Jacqui Smith Fettig

text:
dame susan jocelyn bell burnell (15 july 1943) is an astrophysicist from northern ireland who, as a postgraduate student, co-discovered the first radio pulsars in 1967.
she was credited with "one of the most significant scientific achievements of the 20th century".
the discovery was recognised by the award of the 1974 nobel prize in physics, but despite the fact that she was the first to observe and precisely analyse the pulsars, bell was excluded from the recipients of the prize.
many prominent astronomers criticised bell's omission, including sir fred hoyle.
bell served as president of the royal astronomical society from 2002 to 2004, as president of the institute of physics from october 2008 until october 2010, and as interim president of the institute following the death of her successor, marshall stoneham, in early 2011.
in 2018, she was awarded the special breakthrough prize in fundamental physics.
she gave the whole of the ¬£2.3m prize money to help women, ethnic minority, and refugee students become physics researchers.

text:
why i didn‚Äôt report
.
sexual abuse comes in many forms, some are more subtle others more obvious, all of them are hurtful and traumatizing.
i was a child and it was my all day life, it took me years to understand that it wasn‚Äôt normal and many more years to understand it was sexual abuse. denial is how i‚Äôve been dealing with it to the point i pretended it never happened until about 1 1/2 years ago. only then i learned about post traumatic stress disorder, only then i started to understand my anxiety, my panic attacks, my struggle with self worth and the inability to say no (to only name a few). the day i walked into my psychologists room was the starting point of a journey in which i relived the first 18 years of my life. finally after 15 years of denial i started to look into the hurt, pain and shame that has been eating me from inside out, dominating every single day of my life. on some days i thought it‚Äôll break me again.
when everyone joined into #metoo i still wasn‚Äôt ready to speak, the wounds were just torn open and still bleeding, i was still wearing the shame of my abuse.
.
a couple of weeks ago while talking to one of the very few people who know, i said: i have to own my story. if i want to help others with the same traumas i have to speak up and stop hiding.
.
the #whyididntreport campaign is so important to raise not just awareness for the crimes that are happening everyday to women and men alike, but far more important to raise the awareness why we live in a society in which we are more scared of the reactions, of not being believed, or feeling ashamed than of the person who has hurt us, disrespected us and took away our right to be safe! .
i didn‚Äôt report and i‚Äôm not in a place to say if i ever will. this is a very personal decision for every victim to make, but it is the responsibility of society, the countries we live in, the people who we are surrounded by to create a safe space for every victim to reach out, tell and report the crime that has been done, without judging, without shaming and without being labeled.
.
today i stand up, i speak up and i own my story!
today i stop wearing the shame of my abuse!

text:
i've been guilted into doing things  like most of us, like
.
loving someone or loving them more, when maybe i would have done so myself or had chosen not to because i didn't want to,
.
or
.
guilted into doing things for others when i would have or may have not chosen to because i didn't feel the need that i had to,
.
or
.
guilted into giving more of myself, which maybe i would have volunteered to do anyway or may have chosen not to for a reason that mattered more,
.
in all these situations i gave into the guilt because i thought by not doing so, maybe something was wrong with me or that i would not have looked good or that i'm a bad person if i didn't.
.
if only in each situation i had taken a minute to ask myself what my true intentions were for doing or not doing any of those things, and i listened to my heart to hear what it had to say, and followed its advice, i would have never doubted who i was and  given into the guilt. .
and, if i had chosen to proceed to do the things anyway, it would have been of my own choice.
.
which is a far more powerful place to do something or give something from than choosing to do so from guilt.
.
. .
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
dr. ford, i salute your incredible courage.

if you're still sitting there defiantly telling yourself she made this up, she's just a political pawn, shame on you.

look at the women in your life - your wife, daughter, sister, mother, girlfriends, aunts, nieces, colleagues, office admin, neighbours....the harsh and sad reality is that a staggering percentage of them have or will be victims of sexual or physical abuse in their lifetime.  would you doubt any of them? if they had the courage tell you their story, would you doubt one word?  please, in the name of basic decency, show this well spoken, intelligent, couragous woman the respect she deserves.

text:
in response to a meme i saw on facebook with the caption ‚Äúdoes this look like the face of a woman recounting a sexual assault that has caused her 36 years of pain and suffering‚Äù she was smiling in the photos. i am beyond angry at such post!! here are my thoughts. ***this is about to get real uncomfortable!!!
what a stupid fucking headline this is!!!!!!!!!! yes, it does deserve every single one of those exclamation points... and let me tell you why. what do you suppose a victim of sexual abuse should look like?!!! a sad, over burdened failure of a human? is that what you think she should look like?! truth bomb:
i am a victim of sexual abuse, i was abused as a young child, first time many many people will know this. do i fit the image of  what you think a victim should look like? should i then take down every photo of me smiling? or should i feel guilty if i smile during the day? i did not ever come forward and i did not ever accuse the abuser but let me tell you, should he ever run for office i would 100% be speaking up. i was young but i am not young anymore and i can now choose to tell my story if i want to. so please, this is bullshit, if you think she's lying than that's your opinion but don't ever think for one minute that a victim of abuse walks around with a sad look on their face and a ruined life, because most of us were told to let it go and keep moving and make your life matter. 
this made me cry today, we all need to come together and tell our stories and stop this madness. i stand behind her and every man or woman that has been a victim of abuse. my love and support is with you always. do not stay quiet.
.
.
#metoo #standup #speakup #endthestigma #ibelievechristineblaseyford #womenempowerment

text: have any of you ever been through a season where your heart hangs in the swaying balance of feeling heavy and hard pressed, yet happy and whole at the same time?! the last few weeks, the concept of light :: the need for light in our lives and the ability to see the light in others :: has been a constant thought lately....especially when it comes to being a light, as well as seeing the light in other woman. light‚Äôs purpose is to make bright what is already beautiful, give warmth, create growth and dispel darkness. isn‚Äôt that exactly what each of us not only long to receive, but to also be for others?! when we soften our hearts to see the good and greatness in others, it only propels our hearts to be equally as such. there‚Äôs nothing weak about having a brokenness that allows us to see beauty, brightness and strength in others. when we believe in others and allow others to be truly seen and known, known in their greatness as well as in their short comings, there‚Äôs no room for shame. shame thrives in darkness. we need to stop hurrying to beat others to the punch in pointing out flaws and failures and tearing down, but rather reveling in each other‚Äôs worth. i‚Äôm not speaking right now into the #metoo or #believewomen movement, i‚Äôm just speaking into the basic need for women to start believing in their worthiness, stepping out and standing up from a place of approval, rather than hustling for approval...and breathing that same worthiness into other women. because it‚Äôs that kind of mindset and encouragement, that brings about the biggest change. women who are hurting, often times, hurt other women in their longing for healing...and at some point, someone has to put grace at the forefront and hold out a hand for that hurt heart to hold on to, to break the cycle. this morning as i sit here with coffee in hand and the sun beaming through my windows, i realize how i need to be more of this kind of lady. and in that same thought, i am equally grateful for the ladies in my life who exemplify and live out wholly, this exact brightness üíï‚ú® be bright today!

text: one of the top athletes in the world, #cristianoronaldo, is being accused of an alleged rape 9 years ago. according to e-mails, medical & police reports, the victim originally accused ronaldo of rape in 2009. she said she was too afraid to say his name to the police & to go to court because she feared harassment by ronaldo's fans. the only lawyer she could afford was an unexperienced lawyer (specialised on traffic violations) that made a deal with ronaldo's high-profile lawyers. they settled on $375,000, & the victim had to be silent & never mention the incident ever again. with the #metoo movement currently happening, the victim has a new lawyer who says the settlement is void. he says that she was diagnosed with ptsd & describes the mediation as traumatic.

text:
the greatest failure of [hu]man[s] is to become that which [s]he claims to abhor... your excuses for men who rape are as valid as the excuses for people who hate. if you're more concerned with why women wait so long to speak out vs why so many women have these experiences then your focus is waaaaaaaayyyyyyy off!

what would the world be if instead of checking, blaming accusing, and condemning women for not doing enough to protect ourselves from or prevent rape (or for not speaking out as soon as it happens and providing a full video account, three witnesses, skin from the rapist, surveillance footage, all transcripts of any phone or text messages between you and the rapist, character witnesses, your complete sexual history, and half your soul to prove said rape happened) guys actually checked other guys on rape culture and sexually offensive behaviors towards women? üó£why are you men not talking to other men about why so many women have these horrendous ass stories!?!?! because if it was your daughter......üôÑ stop focusing your efforts on women and focus your efforts to educate men to not be sexual predators! sexual assault was so common growing up i remember sitting around a table of girls in elementary and us talking about our abuse like it was a natural f'n thing and none of us flinched.....wow. i weep for the little girls we left behind....(and the little boys who endure too). #tristadaniell #usa  #blackwriters #blackpoets #rape #metoo #billcosby #kavenaugh #rapesurvivors #truth #opinions #socialcommentary #sexualpredators #sex #consent #monday #writingcommunity #writersofinstagram #commentary #totd #unpopularopinion #untwinemeafrica #mirakee #mysticmessenger #mystic #healer #blacklesbians #lgbt #blackbloggers

text:
i often chose silence because it's more comfortable, because it doesn't make waves, because it eliminates anyone from attacking my truth, because i feel safer, because it's what i have been taught. 
but that's not the whole truth, silence eats at you. silence leaks your power to the person or event that you are silent about. silence robs you of life and joy and freedom. silence makes others comfortable with what they don't want to deal with. silence kills.  it kills dreams, kills childhoods, kills self worth, kills self love, kills relationships, it kills freedom, it kills people. 
thank you to everyone who bravely admittedly to a story of abuse they haven't found their voice to express yet.  every little step matters.  it's easier to choose silence because we're used to it but liberating to let it all go üíñ #ibelieveyou .
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
we are recruiting drop-in volunteers!

we are currently recruiting self-identifying women aged 21 and over to volunteer at our new women-only daytime drop-in in eastbourne.

if you have good listening skills, lots of empathy, a non-judgemental attitude, an interest in supporting survivors and can spare 3-6 hours a month on thursdays please contact katie or liv (contact information below) for more info & for an application pack.

no experience necessary as full in-house training is provided. closing date friday 23rd november 2018, interviews will be held on thursday 6 december.

training dates are as follows:
10am-3pm thursday 10th/17th/24th/31st january 2019 in eastbourne. 
trainees will need to attend all 4 days.

we welcome applications from all sectors of our diverse community and applications from older women, bme or lbt women are particularly encouraged.

contact details:
info@survivorsnetwork.org.uk // 01273 203380

a crossroads.

a moment that determines the trajectory of our lives.
.
not forever - but there‚Äôs a you before the event and a you after the event.

text:
2017 has been a year of many lessons learnt ! for me ,the most life-changing moment was finding my inner voice and inner power.

i have realized that sometimes walking away from disrespect has nothing to do with weakness, and everything to do with strength. i walked away not because i wanted others to realize my worth and value, but because i finally realized my own !!!! i learnt the hard way that i cannot always count on others to respect me and my feelings, even if i respect theirs.being a good person doesn't guarantee that others will be good people too !!! i've learnt that i only have control over myself and how i choose to be as a person. as for others, i can only choose to accept them  and their harmful ways or walk away !  changes are a necessary part of life, and a healthy change is a great thing. 2018,i am so ready for you !!! bvb üôèüèº‚ù§Ô∏è#innerpeace #innocent #innerbeauty #memories#power#feminine #motivation#womensworld #strength #selfhelp#inspire #metoo

text:
one of the times that i was sexually assaulted, i did report it.  during a job interview, the guy doing the interview repeatedly groped me and offered a job in exchange for sex.  when i told family, i was told that these things happen, it wasn't a big deal, and i just needed to get over it and take the job.  when i took the job and reported it to hr, they said it was my word against his, and based on his tenure at the company, they were choosing to take no action.  there was only one person that believed me at the time, and to this day i still have an infinite amount of respect for him because of that.  i quit shortly after because i couldn't stand seeing the guy's slimy smile, but i almost wish i didn't - he was fired a few months later after a couple more sexual harrassment reports were filed against him.  i reported, and was told to get over it and called a liar.  everyone deserves a fair chance to be heard, but often, the victims are silenced.

#metoo #believesurvivors #ididreportandnoonecared #mystory #speakingup #staystrong #whyididntreport

text:
i've had a pattern of some very difficult trying, challenging situations happening over and over again with different circumstances.  i need to look at this with a fine-tooth comb and see what i need to do differently in order to not have these situations come up in my life over and over again with different people with the same scenario. i'm looking at the pattern and willing to make the change.

i know i can't control other people, but what i do have in my control is to look at myself and look at what i need to do differently in order to at least somewhat if not fully have different circumstances in my life in regards to this issue. ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

text:
#asiabennet #asiargento asia argento says the truth
as promised, here the first release of my new blog "a lingua sciolta '.
in this post, however, i want to deliberately abstain from judging asia, which in reality behind a childhood lived as a daughter of characters rather famous and probably, with little time available to make parents ... with a need to live (with a father horror director) from "child artist", on scary sets, staged in chills, at an age where paradoxically a child can not see a horror film but can interpret it ... with an adolescence made of excesses, drugs and tattoos blasphemous ordinary protagonists (see the holy virgin tattooed on the belly) ... of a controversial and scandalous motherhood, for photos risen during pregnancy (although today on the agenda) ... well, despite what i have followed in these years on the sideboard, because of my interest in morgnan (pseudonym of marco castoldi ex husband, singer and musician and the usual bluvertigo) the feeling a character that i never successful to define!
said there after the 2 interviews previous in the usa and in england, finally stasera has arrived to defend from the accusations of sexual practice on child, to the italian tv on the seven channel, by granting a long interview to massimo giletti.
i do not know where is the truth, i invite the judge who should judging her strongly fitness and / or innocence, but personally i have found it credible, suffering neither contradicting and appreciable for having never taken his reputation always discutable.
in conclusion i find personally more doubts in believing a male who seemed to be sitted to be constructed to sexual performance by a woman which is more than strictly or in any strong physically, without nearly a working role which could achieve what power psychological of submission, in addition to the fact of not being nearly physically pleasing.
concludes with solidarity towards #metoo (born from own silver asia) because nobody can allow you to build a woman!

text:
in august, i was invited to speak about the future of #metoo at madsymposium by the very gracious @reneredzepinoma and @melshannondipietro - besides being a great honor, it was a greatly impactful week where i met some inspiring folks who are changing the course of our industry, and our world, in real time and in real action. 
they have posted the video (link in their profile @themadfeed ) of our panel - lead by pulitzer prize writer @kimseverson and by my side the strong speaker with good ideas, @wade_davis28 . 
the other video clips of panels and speakers are well worth your time and energy as well. please take the time to watch, specifically, @dan.giusti talk about his work with his company @brigaid (chefs i‚Äôm looking at you) - he left a deeply important imprint on me, one that i meditate on daily. 
thank you once again to the mad family for creating a space for us to grow and learn. i can not wait to keep contributing in whatever ways, big or small, that i can.

text:
i really dislike the whole typical gender thing that‚Äôs in mostly everyone‚Äôs mindsets. like not just women are feminine and pretty and men are masculine and weird or doesn‚Äôt take care of themselves, and although i‚Äôm a ‚Äúboy‚Äù which i hate saying that word because i really don‚Äôt feel like i belong in the label men man boy. that‚Äôs why i just tell people to call me by my name. i hate being called sir, mr , man , it‚Äôs just really stupid to me. and i say that because mostly everyone thinks that they have both genders figured out, but they don‚Äôt. i am not masculine, i am not stupid because i actually use my brain , i hate sports, i hate trucks, i am not going to drink or do drugs, i don‚Äôt like cutting my hair so i don‚Äôt anymore, i don‚Äôt have a deep voice because i don‚Äôt want to, i don‚Äôt wear shorts, i‚Äôm not dirty i shower almost 3 times a day, i buy specific products that i like for myself ( not old spice, i like dove), i hardly care or think about sex. i dress proper and the way i like. and etc. i would say i‚Äôm gay but i just really think i‚Äôm asexual now i prefer nothing, idk why i‚Äôm just not amused by any gender that much. so i  basically feel like i‚Äôm forced under the word man because i really don‚Äôt feel like that. i mean obviously i‚Äôm a male i don‚Äôt even like using that term. i‚Äôm pretty sure some women and men can relate. so ya that‚Äôs why i prefer everyone to just call me by my name. if you don‚Äôt want to be called under a label that you feel your forced under you don‚Äôt have to be! ps( i don‚Äôt even like my sexual orientation being labeled, i just like being myself). oh and i‚Äôm emotional. my zodiac is a cancer‚ôãÔ∏è. sorry if all of that was very confusing. but if you do take your place and feel like you belong and are comfortable in the label that you are in that‚Äôs very great i‚Äôm not judging‚ù§Ô∏è just please be yourself it would make you happier.

text:
she was eight on a playground when a man
took from her what she could never get back
but she isn‚Äôt your daughter/sister/mother

she was eighteen when a man thought 
saying i love you meant he owned her 
thought her body was his for the taking
but she isn‚Äôt your daughter/mother/sister 
so you won‚Äôt believe her 
she was twenty eight when she told a boyfriend 
every girl has a story they wish they didn‚Äôt 
but she wasn‚Äôt his daughter/mother/sister 
so he wouldn‚Äôt believe her 
she will be too many years old 
and gone too long

text:
part 2
i stepped down from the witness chair and i regretted speaking out because i lost everything and everyone in that courtroom. stepping out of the courtroom, i saw my family hugging my father. his lawyer shook his hand and told him ‚Äúwe got this mr. rolando.‚Äù and there i was alone and waiting outside the courtroom with a social worker by my side more alone than ever and awaiting for the fate of my destiny. a destiny that no matter what the jury and the judge decided on his life, my life was changed forever. i spent the rest of my teenage and young adult years always thinking that i destroyed my family with my disclosure. i felt guilty, ashamed and alone because even though they had wronged me, i loved my family and the pain of abandonment was greater than anything in the world. now, as an advocate, i don‚Äôt regret coming forward with the sexual abuse. now, i understand that i had no other choice. it was either remaining silent and to continue being sexually abused or saving myself or other family members children from suffering sexual abuse at the hands of my father. my family never believed me but they never left their children with him. they were cautious about him. and if that was the only thing that i gained to protect those children, then the sacrifice was well worth it. because when something like sexual abuse or sexual assault comes into the open it should be  taken serious, it should be an automatic alarm sign for everyone. even if there isn‚Äôt no ‚Äúproof‚Äù we should always be alert and cautious with that person. coming forward with the sexual abuse is the most difficult thing to do for survivors.we think about everything before we come forward with the abuse.the shame and the concern about being believed, the concern of being labeled and attacked by people and the terrible losses of our own families and friends.
#storiestotell #survival #childabusesurvivor #sexualabuse #teachersofinstagram #childabuse #metoo #mentoo #survival #justice #whyididreport

text:
last week, i had a life-changing experience. i'm dedicating my posts this week to sharing about it, because this is a turning point for me. i will no longer be silent and complicit in our repression.

i woke up last friday morning emotionally exhausted, tired of feeling triggered, tired of crying over the rawness i felt with everything going on around us. the previous night at therapy, we talked about how i felt watching the supreme court debacle unfold. how it reminds me of the times i was sexually assaulted and harassed. how, when those things happened, i felt powerless because it was "just how things are" for women. how these proceedings reinforce the beliefs that if abuse victims speak up, it only creates more pain, not justice.

so, i decided to join friday's #cancelkavanaugh protests in dc. i didn't know anyone else going, i didn't know where to go or what to do. i felt scared and alone. i wondered if this was the right thing to do, and i almost backed out before i even got dressed.

i sent a group text message to several women i know from @_behold.her to see if anyone in the city wanted to meet up last minute. no one could make it. and i decided that it didn't matter if anyone was with me that i knew. i would be surrounded by people who wanted to be there, who were putting themselves on the line to give victims a voice. i trusted and believed the voice inside of me, the one that has been silenced and shut down for so many years, and i got ready for my first protest since the women's march in 2017.

dressed in all black, wearing my "nasty woman" t-shirt, i made a sign out of a wooden door threshold and repurposed frame mats bearing posters from @soulandinkcrew. as i left the house, messages of support from the behold her community poured in, encouraging me to keep going. to represent. to know that they were with me in spirit.

i left the house, armed with a sign and an unwavering determination to show up for everyone who couldn't be there. what happened next defied my expectations and galvanized me into activism. this day changed me forever.

my story continues in tomorrow's post. thanks for reading.

text:
tw: rape
today has been a hard day.  i woke up at 5am to pregnancy pee, and opened up facebook.  several friends have recounted their rape and assault stories publically since the recent public dissection of ford has been storming social media in attempts to keep a rapist out of senate. 
i've been coping well, strong, thinking about my trauma, contemplating it, postulating its effects on my lifetime here and there, but remaining active in political engagement the best i can, and with little emotion reaction.
until today.  i opened my facebook to another onslaught of rape stories from friends i love, nothing i wasnt anticipating.  and yet, i lost it.  i lost myself in my trauma and slipped into a void of panic attack, a weight crushing down on my chest as i stared at the ceiling in disbelief internally reliving all my violations over and over.  quietly, silently, next to my partner.
he woke up, went downstairs, and i sheepishly followed him, no words would come out because i wanted to ask for help processing but i didnt want to get in the way of his morning routine, and luckily he could tell, and asked me.  i started sobbing, about how i couldn't stop reliving everything, and i spent the next hour reciting just some of my rapes, and assaults out loud.
postulating about which rape hurt me the most, crying, and he held my hand and just let me talk.
my heart pouring, overwhelmed with greif, anger at men that said they respected me, but used me, pretended to be my friends, in order to fuck me.
how the last two occasions fucked me up the most.  how my ex coerced me until i couldn't say no, and how he told me he loved me in the middle of it, on our first date, and how i dont actually remember the sex part of it, just him being on top of me and knowing i didnt want it and i couldn't say no, how he told me after it got him more excited that i resisted him for so long.  that was just the last time i was raped.  not the most violent, but for some reason the one that broke my mind.  and i am just not coping with it all anymore today. 
i hope whoever is hurting today knows i love them, and i'm there with them.  and we can heal together.
#metoo #ptsd #rape #survivor

text:
my short skirt, by eve ensler

it is not an invitation
a provocation
an indication
that i want it
or give it
or that i hook.

my short skirt
is not begging for it
it does not want you
to rip it off me
or pull it down.

my short skirt
is not a legal reason
for raping me
although it has been before
it will not hold up
in the new court.

my short skirt, believe it or not
has nothing to do with you.

my short skirt
is about discovering
the power of my lower calves
about cool autumn air traveling
up my inner thighs
about allowing everything i see
or pass or feel to live inside.

my short skirt is not proof
that i am stupid
or undecided
or a malleable little girl.

my short skirt is my defiance
i will not let you make me afraid
my short skirt is not showing off
this is who i am
before you made me cover it
or tone it down.
get used to it.

my short skirt is happiness
i can feel myself on the ground.
i am here. i am hot.

my short skirt is a liberation
flag in the women's army
i declare these streets, any streets
my vagina's country.

my short skirt
is turquoise water
with swimming colored fish
a summer festival
in the starry dark
a bird calling
a train arriving in a foreign town
my short skirt is a wild spin
a full breath
a tango dip
my short skirt is
initiation
appreciation
excitation.

but mainly my short skirt
and everything under it
is mine.
mine.
mine.

the fact is, you probably don‚Äôt know a woman who doesn‚Äôt have a #metoo story.  and that‚Äôs the problem. my #metoo story doesn‚Äôt define me. of course it wasn‚Äôt my fault. but i will feel culpable if i don‚Äôt say ‚Äústop‚Äù now. this is the end. i refuse to continue accepting you making your desires mean something about me. 
no means no. taking is not asking.  hateful speech about women is violence against people.  my ass does not control you; control yourself.  sexual objectification is not a compliment. 
we are all in this human experience together. we share this time, we share this space, but my body is mine. it‚Äôs here for me and the choice is mine - not yours. teach yourself, teach your children, teach your parents, teach each other. we must learn this now. 
#eveensler #vaginamonologues #myshortskirt #mineminemine

text:
dear human,
imagine a time when a woman's menstrual blood was mysterious ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢
when men bled they would die, but once a month women bled and they lived! (that's some magical shit.)
from there the symbolism created by different cultures, religions, and groups concluded women to be impure and cursed. 
women would congregate in a monthly red tent to support each other, tell stories of their ancestors, celebrate a girl's right of passage into womanhood, and unconditionally love each other. ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ 
today we don't have the luxury of doing this monthly with our sisters, but at mxe it always feels like you're in the red tent. our family celebrates everyone-- from young to wise, from females to males to binary, from black to purple to white to pink.
we may not know your name yet, but you're still our sister/ brother.
we see you,
your mxe family

text: this project has been long awaited..over 25 yrs in the making... not only did @iampennae_salonpennae have an amazing book signing in the hottest location @nars_atlanta_boutique in the shops of buckhead...but she released her first single!!! on the same night... so just a little recap of what you missed...the book signing was not  just a normal boring ass stand in line signing...it was one of a kind ...women were getting their makeup ...live female dj ..endless champagne... chef on the scene,  @sipououi was in the house serving up the best ..@ginabarboza was there with her amazing film crew ...the who's who of atlanta... live band!! its was a party ...and also honored individuals as well as myself for not just working side by side for 26 yrs but for also being the ceo of @soluxepup and other  black business owners in buckhead ... what an amazing night ...so proud of this one right here...so go order your single today on itunes, google play or any music outlet and pick up or order your copy of the book... definitely life changing and inspirational ...always remember you cant hold strong powerful women down of any race or background...hate only motivates!!! so keep moving forward and don't ever let no one stop you!!! continue to have faith in god and continue to have faith in yourself‚ù§ #livepastyourpaintoliveyourdreams #igotmyselftogether #succesatanyage #metoo #blackgirlmagic #browngirls #sistersstandtogether #salonpennae #jennybthebrand #soluxe #author  #sistersinbusiness #buckheadatlanta #buckheadsfinest #buckheadelite #buckheadbeauty

text:
social media spreads news like wild fire. it‚Äôs one of our generations quickest forms of communication. this psa will focus on describing the way that social media influences revolutions in society. as posts on social media are sent out to the world, they have the ability to become ‚Äúviral‚Äù and to influence millions of individuals around our globe. political revolutions and changes have begun to take advantage of the fast-paced influence of the media. social media has become a catalyst for political influence as sides of different revolutions voice their unfiltered opinions regarding the opposite sides. as an example, the #metoo movement become rooted almost entirely in social media, as surviving victims of sexual assault came forward with their stories and shared them with the world. i consider this a revolution because it has completely changed perspectives on sexual assault and brings victims together to support each other. as with most revolutions, the #metoo movement has its recognized leaders, such as asia argento, gywneth paltrow, and jennifer lawrence. 
my focus now shifts to muhammed muheisen, a photographer for national geographic and two-time pulitzer prize winner. muheisen is a perfect example of an individual using social media platforms to spark a social movement and revolution. as a photographer, he has great popularity and influence. he has over 398k followers on instagram and his photos capture the brutal hardships of a suffering part of our world. muheisen started everydayrefugees non-profit as a way to educate the world about the harsh realities faced by refugees and internally displaced individuals around the globe. his photos are trending and viral all throughout social media and spark emotions of sadness, sympathy, and a desire to provoke change. his photos can make you feel even uncomfortable in my opinion. however, that‚Äôs the whole goal. we should not be normalizing this crisis or its tragedies.the refugee crisis and others like it can be an easy thing to try to ignore due to the fact that the crisis is taking place mainly overseas. activists like muheisen fight to make sure that we don‚Äôt forget, but instead remember the suffering and join

text:
call it what it was!! üíú. repeat after me, i never said #no i just laid there looking out the window of his truck at the moon with tears rolling down my face.

after i pulled my pants back up that he had pulled down to my knees without asking i still sat there saying nothing. 
perhaps he forgot the first thing i said to him was that i didn't want to have sex!!! maybe the long dirt path along a corn field that lead into a clearing in the woods was just a place he liked and not a place he could force me to do what he wanted.

every second of that very long 3 minutes of my 16th year i never #screamed said #no #stop #nomeansno #didntfightback i didnt do any of that because i thought if i didn't fight back, if i didn't scream #no then he couldn't #rapeme 
#rapevictim after 17 years of forcing myself to believe i didn't get raped because i choose to not get raped. i was 16 and in a guys truck that had just shook my dad's hand before we had dinner.... then ended up down a dirt path in the woods where i knew no one. i didn't have a cell phone to call home! i was scared. and in that split second i choose to be what i thought was #weak  and just lay there not saying a word sobbing as quietly as i could.

my first #therapysession made me see a few things... but the biggest revelation was the fact that it was #notmyfsult and that i #chose to let him hurt me a little bit and not a lot. and at 16 that was the best decision i could have made for the fear he would have taken it anyway and then left me there!

i didn't consider myself a victim because i didn't say no!! and other men women and children are raped daily and it is horrific. but in my own small situation i was a #victim 
now maybe i can let that go forever and help others see that not wanting sex after you've had sex is different that forcing yourself to lay there until he's done so that you don't feel even more violated, are not the same thing!! take care all üíú
#depression or #anxiety doesn't have to take every single day of your life away from you. 
this journey for myself is scary but i hope it helps, and i hope my journey helps someone else üíúüíú
#rape is something that never really goes away!
#metoo

text:
my life as a woman this week:
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
sunday: i go to a job interview. i‚Äôm the only woman in the room‚Ä¶ do i wear my hair up or down? do i wear a skirt or pants? how do i navigate this space? i feel intimated but i have to project confidence. is this what the rest of my career will feel like?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
monday: i‚Äôm biking home from class. my friend forces me to take her mace, she‚Äôs so nervous for me. i laugh and tell her its fine‚Ä¶ but i still take the mace.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
tuesday: i learn to negotiate salary. why is it so low? what did i do wrong? how much am i worth? how do i convince them of that? how do i balance boldness with respect? how big/small do i need to be here?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
wednesday: i experience sexual harassment in class because i forgot to turn the airdrop off on my computer‚Ä¶ i didn‚Äôt know i needed to pay attention to that too. who sent me this? why? who can i trust? i feel targeted, i feel vulnerable, i feel shame. i pretend it didn‚Äôt happen and try to focus on my work.

text:
this. 
men ask why women are so pissed off. even guys with wives and daughters. jackson katz, a prominent social researcher, illustrates why. he's done it with hundreds of audiences: "i draw a line down the middle of a chalkboard, sketching a male symbol on one side and a female symbol on the other.
then i ask just the men: what steps do you guys take, on a daily basis, to prevent yourselves from being sexually assaulted? at first there is a kind of awkward silence as the men try to figure out if they've been asked a trick question. the silence gives way to a smattering of nervous laughter. occasionally, a young a guy will raise his hand and say, 'i stay out of prison.' this is typically followed by another moment of laughter, before someone finally raises his hand and soberly states, 'nothing. i don't think about it.'
then i ask the women the same question. what steps do you take on a daily basis to prevent yourselves from being sexually assaulted? women throughout the audience immediately start raising their hands. as the men sit in stunned silence, the women recount safety precautions they take as part of their daily routine.
hold my keys as a potential weapon. look in the back seat of the car before getting in. carry a cell phone. don't go jogging at night. lock all the windows when i sleep, even on hot summer nights. be careful not to drink too much. don't put my drink down and come back to it; make sure i see it being poured. own a big dog. carry mace or pepper spray. have an unlisted phone number. have a man's voice on my answering machine. park in well-lit areas. don't use parking garages. don't get on elevators with only one man, or with a group of men. vary my route home from work. watch what i wear. don't use highway rest areas. use a home alarm system. don't wear headphones when jogging. avoid forests or wooded areas, even in the daytime. don't take a first-floor apartment. go out in groups. own a firearm. meet men on first dates in public places. make sure to have a car or cab fare. don't make eye contact with men on the street. make assertive eye contact with men on the street.‚Äù ‚Äï jackson katz, the macho paradox: why some men hurt women and how

text:
i received a lot of messages yesterday about blacking out my profile picture to show men what the world would be like without women.

i don't vibe with that. 
i stand in solidarity with all the women of the world. i stand in solidarity against domestic violence. i stand in solidarity against the abuse of the patriarchy.

but i will not make myself invisible. i will not be silenced. i will not hide.

the patriarchy wants women to "black out". they want us to be quiet. they want us to stop sharing our stories. they want us to stop shining our lights. they don't care what the world would be like without us because they do not value us.

in protect against domestic violence, in protest for women, in protest against the patriarchy, i believe we need to shine brighter.

and honestly, i don't believe changing our profile pictures will teach anyone anything. no man is going to be like "wow, now that all these profile pictures are black, i can really understand how women are valuable to society. i think i'll start respecting them more!". all the men we would be trying to "teach" will either not care at all or laugh at us.

keep speaking your truth women. keep shining your lights. keep making them hear you. do not black yourself out. do not remove yourself from the situation. stand firm, shine bright, and express your beautiful goddess self. if anything will change the situation between men and women, that will do it.

#noblackout #shinebright #iwonthide #solidarity #goddess #wombman #metoo #tellyourstory #beheard #beseen #beauthentic #standup #rise #sacredfeminine #divinefeminine

text:
‚Äúwomen who seek to be equal to men lack ambition.‚Äù when i heard @sarah.arbi say that, i didn‚Äôt know how to take it. did she mean all the suffragettes lacked ambition? did it mean i lack ambition? but then she explained to me her thought process, and it blew my mind. she said ‚Äútoday we need to set our own rules and our values because the current system has low and outdated standards for both genders. once we completely revolutionize and challenge the old system, without seeking to work within it, we will be respected. the first step was to seek equality, we wanted to be treated as humans and not sold/ bought we wanted to vote we wanted to work. now we have have proven that we can do a ‚Äúmans job‚Äù in the workforce and we can simultaneously do a ‚Äúwoman‚Äôs job‚Äù at home, but what we need to be respected is to not play by the rules of the current system, and instead of trying to do both jobs, just completely change the job description. the standards are low and it‚Äôs up to us to raise them.‚Äù sarah‚Äôs story is on a ted talk - and it will give some background on how a scientist went into communication and is now being asked to teach the subject because she just excels at whatever she puts her mind to. her life has not been easy but she still manages to radiate pure love. she is a woman that inspires me and hopefully this inspires you too. #amalsbossbabes 
#feminism #equality #metoo #iamanastywoman #iamwithher #everydaysexism #heforshe #letstalk #whyistayed #yesallwomen #tothegirls #allmencan #effyourbeautystandards #arabwoman #young_arab_media_leaders

text:
i‚Äôm taking a break from social media for a while. i‚Äôm sad that it‚Äôs come to this for me but it‚Äôs the best thing i can do - since stepping up my online activism and advocacy for mental health in my vlogs and great causes like the #metoo movement i have received a lot of love and support from you all, and i‚Äôm grateful. however the increasing amounts of mockery of such just causes, at the expense of those who have suffered great trauma as well as the vile and slut-shaming remarks from men on the internet that think i should ‚Äògo kill myself‚Äô isn‚Äôt something i am in a place to deal with right now with my own mental health. 
sharing my experiences and eliminating stigma is so important to me, and so i‚Äôll return. hopefully when i do the world isn‚Äôt still accepting hate as the norm and the world has become a more open minded, accepting and kinder place where people actually support important causes and have empathy for their fellow human beings. 
but today, at this moment, i seriously doubt that. peace out ‚úåüèª

text:
üí•joy is the highest form of resistance üí• 
although last week was palpably painful and difficult for so many of us as a collective, i refuse to carry that weight on my shoulders as i move forward. i refuse to blackout my profile picture to make a statement and instead, i dare to be seen. i dare to take space. i dare to make clear that my trauma from sexual abuse, sexism, racism, classism etc, does not define me and can therefore not steal my joy. it cannot contain my laughter or shake my inner peace. i will not let it weigh me down. i dare to rise. 
i dare to do so not in ignorance, but in fierce love for everyone around me who can‚Äôt rise, because i know that stepping in joy is stepping in power for them too. i will not give up my own strength by letting anger and hurt define me. 
i dare to find my self-worth beyond my trauma. i dare to tell others that their traumas do not have to ‚Äúmatch‚Äù or ‚Äúexceed‚Äù my own to be worthy or to be heard. this is not a competition, all trauma is relative and worthy and you do not need to have lived my life to ‚Äúsee‚Äù me. so here i am. i dare to be seen. i dare for you to see me how i love myself most: mouth open, smiling, in a child-sized fresh prince t-shirt (that barely fits me)and my favorite polka dot tights. i hope you dare to be seen too ‚ù§Ô∏è #daretobeseen #believesurvivors #metoo #selfworth #activism #takespace #resist #fresh #freshprinceofbelair #reframetheeffoutofit

text:
thank you #metoo movement, today i have the strength to share my story too.

i am not blaming men for what happened to me but i do find it very difficult to forgive their actions, in particular, those two men who have sexually abused me. 
i get that lust is uncontrollable but please listen to our story, for there you will learn the consequences of your actions. like you, we women have been gifted the breath of life to be a part of this world, and i am certain that this is not for us to live in shame and fear, just because you cannot control your lust for desires of the flesh.

linda thompson

text:
üåø read the cation üåø
i love her for many reasons
one of them is this
she understands
i don't need to explain to her
why i wake up
in the middle of the night
and spend the rest in the shower
why i cry sometimes in my sleep
but don't remember why the next morning
i think she loves me too
for the way i don't ask why
one day she wakes up
and gentle touches that were fine yesterday
will propel her into a panic attack today
the blind leading the blind
isn't at all too bad,
when the last thing you want
is to look at the world.
- survivors

text: active listening is one of the best ways to communicate with others. when you listen in an active manner, you hear not only the words of the speaker but you strive to understand their intended meaning. by choosing not to interrupt or formulate conclusions while someone is still speaking to you, you give yourself the opportunity to truly understand what is being said to you. rather than just the cadence of someone's speech and their words, you can take into account body language, tone of voice, and what you know about them. active listening can bring you closer to others because your rapt attention allows you to connect with them. when you listen to others in an active way today, you will be able to understand them at a soul level. #activelistening #soulspeak #consciouslanguage #speakyourtruth #metoo

text:
~~~spreadinglovespreadinglight~~~‚Äùreclaiming my power ‚Äù~~~mrs. ford‚Äôs testimony triggered many memories for me. the last few days have been tough. over the course of my life, i have been subjected to many incidences of sexual harassment and abuse. one of these sexual harassment 'situations' occurred in college.  i was an international student and one of the only black, west indians on a mostly white campus. my major was art and i worked as an artist model to help pay my bills. the unwanted advances came from an artist who sketched and sculpted from my nude poses on a daily basis.  i lived with my white boyfriend off-campus. he was one of the artists who worked alongside the harasser, who was also white.  when i told my boyfriend about his advances he blew it off. he did not want it to affect his job.  i was left to handle the situation: a lone black, west indian woman standing day after day, no longer nude but naked, in the midst of a class of white, tobacco chewing, cigar smoking college professors and their acolytes.  the abuser was in his element.  he found excuses to touch me under the ruse of adjusting the pose without anyone in that room noticing. who would believe me? it finally all came to ahead when i punched him in the face. by this time he had taken his groping off-campus and into my living room, invited by my clueless and gullible boyfriend. he apparently thought that this black woman was for hire because i was living with a white man.  he was wrong.
 i took my complaint to the school and to the dean of students who took me seriously. i was kicked out of the art department and lost my job.  at arbitration my boyfriend stood on the side of the abuser and his professors. i stood alone. i won the case but lost my relationship. no one spoke a word about race but it was insidiously yet explicitly present at all times. today i stand strong as i continue to reclaim my life~~~#metoo #reclaimyourlife #survivor #speak #woke #honesty #truth #standup #fightback #afropunk #blackwomen #pushthrough #staystrong #clarity #awareness #presence #healing #recovery #now #here #yoga #yogacommunity #love #selflove #selfesteem #personalgrowth #selfrespect #confidence #art‚ù§

text:
it's time to step into the fire and die to the old ways.

pluto the transformer goes direct in capricorn, purging another layer of the collective shadow lurking within institutions, government and commerce.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
what we release, we can transmute.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
what we tear down, we can rebuild.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
the evolving soul of humanity demands we step up and step into the fire.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
give up the old power games and the obsessive-compulsive thirst for control.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
rip off the band-aid that's patched it all together and plunge, soul-first, into the wound.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
scrub out the darkest corners and meet the dragons and demons.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
there's no way out but through.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
as the fates of men who seek to hold office, positions of justice, or leadership hang in the balance, pluto assures us that their time will come.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
venus, goddess of love, is about to go retrograde in early scorpio, close to the point that jupiter crossed when the #metoo movement unleashed its voice last year.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
amidst the media sorcery pushing and pulling on the collective feminine pain body as stories of rape, trauma and abuse are shared, a cathartic release of old, toxic energy is rising.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it's time.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it's time those in positions of power owned the responsibility of their positions, rather than abusing their privileges.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
it's time to admit that if our systems are maintained by people without integrity, then it will all crumble.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
in time.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
last week's equinox pitted patriarchal saturn in capricorn against the wounded warrior chiron in aries, with the sun and mercury in justice-seeking libra holding the balance.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
bravery, courage, harmony and justice are facing off against the status quo.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
offer it all to the raging fire.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
justice will be done.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
not by hiding our faces or disappearing from view.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
but by looking eye to eye.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
by calling on pluto: do your work.

it's time.

text:
i will not be blacking out my profile picture. however well meaning it may seem, i am tired of being told to be quiet and small, tired of our voices being erased and tired of whittling myself away to make others comfortable. i am here to be as visible as possible and to take up as much space as i can. 
if you do want to black out your profile picture on social media, may i respectfully suggest that you make a small donation to a womens, lgbtqia or survivors advocacy group and post that on your profile instead. 
be strong. we see you. .

i will not be blacking out my profile picture. however well meaning it may seem, i am tired of being told to be quiet and small, tired of our voices being erased and tired of whittling myself away to make others comfortable. i am here to be as visible as possible and to take up as much space as i can. 
if you do want to black out your profile picture on social media, may i respectfully suggest that you make a small donation to a womens, lgbtqia or survivors advocacy group and post that on your profile instead. 
be strong. we see you. .

text: was i pre disposed to this illness ‚Äî bipolar? maybe. yet there is no diagnosed history of mental illness in my lineage. perhaps trauma, abuse, harassment, etc triggered my downward spiral. in my first year of university, at the tender age of 17, i was brutally assaulted by a person of authority (not police of emergency services!). the isolation that followed; the shame; the hate; hit me damn hard. after wrestling away from the situation i was forced into, i attempted suicide...on christmas eve. in critical care, my liver was failing and i could barely take a breath without machines helping me. vomit spewed everywhere, my heart rate was sky-high. i was unconscious for a lot of it. the doctor said she‚Äôd never witnessed someone survive a toxicity as high as mine. i was a miracle. i was given the gift of life that year. and i vow to use this precious gift that should have ended, to passionately pursue social work; fight for the rights of marginalized; advocate for better resources; and provide supports for the struggling. i won‚Äôt relent until the work is done, and it will never be done. i am a survivor, and if you‚Äôre reading this so are you. use this beautiful life to get out there and make your mark. together change happens. yes. #bipolar #bipolardisorder #depression #quotes #lovelife #thegiftoflife #socialwork #socialworker #healthinhealthcare #passion #passionate #poem #poetry #poemporn #suicide #suicideawareness #relentless #abuse #harrassment #notokay #metoo #isolation #fear #fearisaliar #makeamark #makeadifference #spokenword #spokenwordpoetry

here i'm in front of a new door after the inspiring pwn offsite where all the mentoring directors have been brain storming all together. together with the aim to connect, to learn and to get inspired from each other. 
and i'm pausing. what's next is now close. 
i love the process of taking the directions that provides me lightness, playfulness and inspirational energies.

text: this is a picture of me from middle school, that's when it all happened. due to recent events i have been motivated and inspired to share a couple of my own personal experiences with violence and sexual assault against women. when i was in 7th grade i was randomly attacked by a boy who was my best friend at the time. we were in theatre together, we would go to speech competitions together, we won trophies together, we would go to the movies together, we would eat lunch together, we were inseparable. one day he snapped, maybe it was because i was attempting to give him relationship advice, but he pushed me into a dark hallway and choked me with both hands. i remember looking straight into his eyes and being in shock that someone i loved so much could do this to me. i did the only thing i could which was knee him in the stomach and i ran into the nearest girl's restroom and cried. i came forward about it, my parents and i reported it to my school. they did nothing, and they even reprimanded me for defending myself. half the school believed my story, the other half thought i was making it up for attention. it ruined me emotionally and i started drinking heavily. the next school year both me and the boy who attacked me ended up going to different schools, we would still see each other at theatre competitions until our senior year of high school. he always greeted me with a smile and a hug, and he made it a point to tell me how pretty i looked and how proud he was of me. the last time i saw him he was playing a minor role in a netflix movie which was actually pretty good. in 8th grade i went to a small get together with a friend and i got extremely intoxicated to the point where i blacked out. i came to with someone who i had considered a friend on top of me. i couldn't remember how i got myself in the position that i was in, but i immediately didn't want to be there anymore. i pushed him off of me and left walking to another friend's house. i left in such a hurry that i accidentally forgot my purse, and i was mortified when i had to go back to pick it up the next day. (see comments section for the rest of the story.) #metoo #whyididntreport #endviolenceagainstwomen

text:
#cristianoronaldo allegedly apologised to model after raping her.
.
.
#cristiano ronaldo allegedly raped a us #model and then said ‚Äúsorry, i‚Äôm usually a gentleman‚Äù, according to court papers filed in las vegas which the star has branded ‚Äúfake news‚Äù, daily mail reports

kathryn mayorga, a 34-year-old teacher who was an aspiring model at the time of the alleged assault, claims ronaldo raped her in a bathroom at the palms hotel and casino in #lasvegas in the early hours of june 13, 2009.
.
.
the ex-man  united, 33, player spoke out in a video on #instagram just hours after her lawyer filed court documents about the case. grinning into the camera, he said, ‚Äòno, no, no, no, no. what they said today? fake, fake news.‚Äô
.
.
according to documents filed at clark county district court on #friday, the #footballer invited mayorga and a #friend to his penthouse suite ‚Äúto enjoy the view of the las vegas strip‚Äù. mayorga claims she refused to get into his hot tub because she did not want to ruin her dress, then ronaldo offered her some athletic shorts and a t-shirt and pointed her towards a bathroom where she could change.
the court documents state that as she was changing, ronaldo entered the bathroom, exposed himself and asked her to perform a sex act.
the striker then turned mayorga on to her side, and that even though she was screaming ‚Äúno, no, no!‚Äù, she was raped by the star.
the documents claim ronaldo left the bedroom after the assault, ‚Äústating he was sorry, he was usually a gentleman‚Äù... she later hired a lawyer, and in 2010 negotiated a ¬£287,000 out-of-court settlement. as part of that deal, she agreed never to go public with her allegations. she is now saying that she only signed the settlement because she was ‚Äúterrified of retaliation‚Äô from ronaldo.
.
